1. The letter J. Since the character i was employed to denote both a vowel and also a consonant, which, it is probable, had the sound of an English y, the Augustan poets permitted themselves occasionally to give it the force of a consonant in certain words in which it properly represented a vowel. Thus the words, abietibus, parietibus, which as quinquesyllables, with the first four short, would be inadmissible in Dactylic verse, were pronounced and scanned as quadrisyllables, abjetibus, parjetibus, the first syllable being now made long by position.
